{"parse":{"title":"Law Against Rehabilitation of Nazism","pageid":56782866,"revid":851301631,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Law Against Rehabilitation of Nazism</b> is a Russian <a href=\"/wiki/Memory_laws\" title=\"Memory laws\">memory law</a> of 2014. It also known as Yarovaya Law, after a Russian politician (<a href=\"/wiki/Irina_Yarovaya\" title=\"Irina Yarovaya\">Irina Yarovaya</a>) who was instrumental in passing it.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The law was originally proposed in 2009. It was approved by the <a href=\"/wiki/Russian_parliament\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Russian parliament\">Russian parliament</a> in April 2014, and signed into law by <a href=\"/wiki/President_of_Russia\" title=\"President of Russia\">President of Russia</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Vladimir_Putin\" title=\"Vladimir Putin\">Vladimir Putin</a> in May that year.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Contents\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Contents</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Criticism\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Criticism</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Applications\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Applications</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Contents\">Contents</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Law_Against_Rehabilitation_of_Nazism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Contents\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The law introduced Article 354.1 to the <a href=\"/wiki/Criminal_Code_of_the_Russian_Federation\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Criminal Code of the Russian Federation\">Criminal Code of the Russian Federation</a>, making it a criminal offense \"to deny facts recognized by the international military tribunal that judged and punished the major war criminals of the European Axis countries [this refers to the <a href=\"/wiki/Nuremberg_trials\" title=\"Nuremberg trials\">Nuremberg trials</a>], to approve of the crimes this tribunal judged, and to spread intentionally false information about the Soviet Union\u2019s activities during World War II\" as well as \"the spreading of information on military and memorial commemorative dates related to Russia\u2019s defense that is clearly disrespectful of society, and to publicly desecrate symbols of Russia\u2019s military glory\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The penalty incurred for violating this law is a fine of up to 500,000 rubles (about USD$8,200 as of April 19, 2018) or a prison terms of up to five years, with a ban from certain posts and professions for another three years, and/or up to one year of community service.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Criticism\">Criticism</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Law_Against_Rehabilitation_of_Nazism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Criticism\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The law has been the subject of domestic and international criticism, due to fears of its impact on <a href=\"/wiki/Free_speech\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Free speech\">free speech</a> and historical research.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> A BBC report in 2017 noted that the law has \"curbed...the public discussion of WW2 history\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:5_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:5-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  <a href=\"/wiki/Human_Rights_Watch\" title=\"Human Rights Watch\">Human Rights Watch</a> report in 2017 noted that \"[the law's] selective implementation has so far led to several unjust sentences\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>  \n</p><p>Russian government officials have dismissed these objections, noting that the law is similar to many other laws known as <a href=\"/wiki/Laws_against_Holocaust_denial\" title=\"Laws against Holocaust denial\">laws against Holocaust denial</a>, particularly common in Europe.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Historian Ivan Kurilla addressed that, saying that while the first European memory laws \"were propagated by left-wing political forces aiming to preserve the memory of oppressed groups and the crimes of their states\", newer laws, such as the Russian one, are increasingly \"backed by pro-state right-wing politicians that seek to create a heroic national narrative and legislate away any doubt about the state\u2019s historical righteousness\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Historian <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nikolay_Koposov&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Nikolay Koposov (page does not exist)\">Nikolay Koposov</a> wrote that the main goal of the law is \"to promote the cult of the Russian state, whose primary incarnation rests in the celebration of the heroic memory of World War II\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Koposov2017_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Koposov2017-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Applications\">Applications</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Law_Against_Rehabilitation_of_Nazism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Applications\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Shortly after its passage, the law was used to convict Russian blogger Vladimir Luzgin, who compared the September 1939 <a href=\"/wiki/German_invasion_of_Poland\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"German invasion of Poland\">German invasion of Poland</a> to the <a href=\"/wiki/Soviet_invasion_of_Poland\" title=\"Soviet invasion of Poland\">Soviet invasion of Poland</a> and referred to the <a href=\"/wiki/Molotov%E2%80%93Ribbentrop_Pact\" title=\"Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact\">Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact</a>, writing on Russian social media platform <a href=\"/wiki/VKontakte\" title=\"VKontakte\">VKontakte</a> that \"communism and Nazism closely collaborated\". Prosecutors accused him of knowingly posting material that may worsen people's view of the Soviet Union, and the court agreed, stating that he had falsified history by stating \"that the communists and Germany jointly attacked Poland, unleashing World War Two, or in other words, that Communism and Nazism co-operated honestly\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:5_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:5-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-:4_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:4-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Luzgin was fined 200 thousand rubles (roughly equivalent to USD$5,000 in 2014) for \"circulation of false information about the activities of the USSR during the years of World War II\", though, as was noted by human rights expert <a href=\"/wiki/Jacob_Mchangama\" title=\"Jacob Mchangama\">Jacob Mchangama</a>, this claim was \"essentially, factually correct\". <sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_4-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> In 2016 Lugzin appealed his case to the <a href=\"/wiki/European_Court_of_Human_Rights\" title=\"European Court of Human Rights\">European Court of Human Rights</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In April 2015, Russian journalist Polina Petruseva was fined 1,000 rubles (USD$16) for posting on the social media platform VKontakte a historical picture showing German Nazi troops in Russia, a picture otherwise available from, among others, <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia\" title=\"Wikipedia\">Wikipedia</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> That same month, a number of Russian bookstores stopped selling the anti-Nazi graphic novel <i><a href=\"/wiki/Maus\" title=\"Maus\">Maus</a></i> because of a swastika appearing on its cover design.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_11-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> A toy store selling toy soldiers in wartime German uniforms was also investigated, and a museum displaying anti-Nazi Soviet posters, showing for example crushed swastikas, decided to censor all swastikas on its exhibits.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Works of two British historians, <a href=\"/wiki/Antony_Beevor\" title=\"Antony Beevor\">Antony Beevor</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/John_Keegan\" title=\"John Keegan\">John Keegan</a>, were banned in one of Russia's regions as the authorities accused them of being influenced by <a href=\"/wiki/Propaganda_in_Nazi_Germany\" title=\"Propaganda in Nazi Germany\">Nazi propaganda</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:4_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:4-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> A month later, another Russian journalist, Sergei Vilkov, was fined 1,000 rubles for posting a caricature on VKontakte (in 2011), which combined the logo of the <a href=\"/wiki/United_Russia\" title=\"United Russia\">United Russia</a> and a swastika.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Law_Against_Rehabilitation_of_Nazism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Presidential_Commission_of_the_Russian_Federation_to_Counter_Attempts_to_Falsify_History_to_the_Detriment_of_Russia%27s_Interests\" title=\"Presidential Commission of the Russian Federation to Counter Attempts to Falsify History to the Detriment of Russia&#39;s Interests\">Presidential Commission of the Russian Federation to Counter Attempts to Falsify History to the Detriment of Russia's Interests</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Law_Against_Rehabilitation_of_Nazism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Belavusau, Uladzislau; Gliszczy\u0144ska-Grabias, Aleksandra (2017-10-19). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=0-w0DwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA293\"><i>Law and Memory: Towards Legal Governance of History</i></a>. Cambridge University Press. p.&#160;293. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781107188754\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781107188754\">9781107188754</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Law+and+Memory%3A+Towards+Legal+Governance+of+History&amp;rft.pages=293&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2017-10-19&amp;rft.isbn=9781107188754&amp;rft.aulast=Belavusau&amp;rft.aufirst=Uladzislau&amp;rft.au=Gliszczy%C5%84ska-Grabias%2C+Aleksandra&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.co.kr%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D0-w0DwAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPA293&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALaw+Against+Rehabilitation+of+Nazism\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:2-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Kurilla, Ivan (August 2014). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.ponarseurasia.org/sites/default/files/policy-memos-pdf/Pepm331_Kurilla_August2014_0.pdf\">\"The Implications of Russia's Law against the \"Rehabilitation of Nazism<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i>PONARS Eurasia Policy Memo No. 331</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=PONARS+Eurasia+Policy+Memo+No.+331&amp;rft.atitle=The+Implications+of+Russia%E2%80%99s+Law+against+the+%22Rehabilitation+of+Nazism%22&amp;rft.date=2014-08&amp;rft.aulast=Kurilla&amp;rft.aufirst=Ivan&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ponarseurasia.org%2Fsites%2Fdefault%2Ffiles%2Fpolicy-memos-pdf%2FPepm331_Kurilla_August2014_0.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALaw+Against+Rehabilitation+of+Nazism\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:1-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_3-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.rt.com/politics/154332-russia-nazi-rehabilitation-ban/\">\"Duma passes bill criminalizing rehabilitation of Nazism\"</a>. <i>RT International</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-03-08</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=RT+International&amp;rft.atitle=Duma+passes+bill+criminalizing+rehabilitation+of+Nazism&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.rt.com%2Fpolitics%2F154332-russia-nazi-rehabilitation-ban%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALaw+Against+Rehabilitation+of+Nazism\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_4-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/10/02/first-they-came-for-the-holocaust-deniers-and-i-did-not-speak-out/\">\"First They Came for the Holocaust Deniers, and I Did Not Speak Out\"</a>. <i>Foreign Policy</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-03-08</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Foreign+Policy&amp;rft.atitle=First+They+Came+for+the+Holocaust+Deniers%2C+and+I+Did+Not+Speak+Out&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fforeignpolicy.com%2F2016%2F10%2F02%2Ffirst-they-came-for-the-holocaust-deniers-and-i-did-not-speak-out%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALaw+Against+Rehabilitation+of+Nazism\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:5-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:5_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:5_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://meduza.io/en/news/2016/07/01/russian-court-convicts-man-of-falsifying-history-for-saying-the-ussr-shares-responsibility-for-starting-wwii\">\"Russian court convicts man of 'falsifying history' for saying the USSR shares responsibility for starting WWII\"</a>. <i>Meduza</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-03-08</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_